00:04:16,819 --> 00:04:20,260
So I just wanted to let you know, give you a little background, right?

57
00:04:20,320 --> 00:04:22,922
So this is not just obviously a Medfit problem.

58
00:04:22,942 --> 00:04:32,927
This is an urban area problem that most of us Board of Health Directors like to talk about all the time and discuss ideas and ways that we're dealing with it.

59
00:04:33,387 --> 00:04:37,609
But we've been dealing with this since obviously for several years now, right?

60
00:04:38,549 --> 00:04:44,793
So in late 2020, we introduced the Clean Up, Seal Up initiative, which was really focused on educating

61
00:04:46,233 --> 00:05:00,220
homeowners and businesses and renters about you know what they could do as far as being compliant with some of our regulations, and also, you know, preventing road infestations on their properties.

62
00:05:01,140 --> 00:05:03,621
It was a really big push around education.

63
00:05:05,222 --> 00:05:13,528
And also at that time we began baiting source and other public properties we weren't dealing with private residential properties at that time.

64
00:05:14,448 --> 00:05:21,033
We did see a lot of success with that and that that has continued in 2021.

65
00:05:22,194 --> 00:05:31,120
The council approved our rodent control ordinance to introduce further efforts, and that required all construction and demolition projects.

66
00:05:31,820 --> 00:05:45,165
dumpster permit holders, food establishments, haulers, and all street opening permits to submit what's called an integrated pest management or an IPM plan, which details prevention methods that they're going to be taking.

67
00:05:45,225 --> 00:05:58,969
So all of the demolition and construction projects are required to initiate these prevention measures at least two weeks prior to the project and to continue throughout the project and weeks after, if necessary.

68
00:06:01,390 --> 00:06:23,141
And then in August of 22, we further stepped up our programming, and we partnered with a pest control company to help us mitigate rodent issues on residential properties using their borrower X treatments, which is basically a carbon dioxide into rodent burrows, which basically suffocates them.

69
00:06:24,402 --> 00:06:27,143
We did not go with the baiting or the

70
00:06:28,704 --> 00:06:40,512
Odenticide, because at that time there, you know, we feel that that's not the appropriate measures to be taking, especially, you know, when we know that there are other animals like such as that unfortunate incident.

71
00:06:41,833 --> 00:06:49,138
So we stayed away from the odenticide on residential properties, but we are doing the borrower X treatments for those who have borrows on their properties.

72
00:06:51,971 --> 00:07:03,755
The rodent ordinance really had a huge impact, we think, and while we're still reviewing and looking at ways to improve, we now review all building projects through CitizenServe.

73
00:07:04,036 --> 00:07:17,981
All projects are sent to the health department for review, and we make sure that anyone that meets the requirements of the ordinance, we ensure that their educated pest management plan is put in place throughout the duration of the project.

74
00:07:19,181 --> 00:07:22,624
We also permit all dumpsters, permanent dumpsters and temporary dumpsters.

75
00:07:23,444 --> 00:07:29,949
The ordinance requires permanent dumpsters submit IPMs to the Board of Health as well, prior to their permanent renewal.

76
00:07:30,790 --> 00:07:47,002
And again, that's an effort to make sure that dumpsters are maintained appropriately, that they're clean, that they're plugged, that they're also that they have an IPM plan in place to ensure that the rodents are kept at bay.

77
00:07:48,901 --> 00:08:00,707
We've always required food establishments to have pest management, but the again the ordinance requires them to submit their IPM which is a full plan it's not just like a pest control report.

78
00:08:01,548 --> 00:08:07,491
It's a full plan on how they, they plan to mitigate issues in the on their establishments.

79
00:08:08,371 --> 00:08:16,353
So to date, since January, we've the Board of Health has received and reviewed 462 IP implants.

80
00:08:18,014 --> 00:08:21,535
And we are still looking for compliance from several others.

81
00:08:21,915 --> 00:08:27,577
And, again, you know, fines will ensue if if folks do not comply.

82
00:08:28,277 --> 00:08:32,498
But we've been pretty good at getting compliance for most of our establishments.

83
00:08:37,330 --> 00:08:52,715
So again, complaints and inspections to date from January 2023, we've received about 213 complaints of those, those are residential and commercial properties, 153 complaints have been closed.

84
00:08:53,295 --> 00:08:58,517
They've been inspected, and if needed, our pest control company has gone out and done borrower RX.

85
00:08:59,017 --> 00:09:03,499
We do not do borrower RX on commercial properties, only residential properties.

86
00:09:04,079 --> 00:09:08,881
If it's a commercial property, we order them to get their own pest control management company in there.

87
00:09:10,932 --> 00:09:12,473
And 52 is still in process.

88
00:09:12,634 --> 00:09:22,981
That means they've been inspected, they've been either referred to the pest control company, or we're in process of getting compliance with the homeowners or the business.

89
00:09:23,001 --> 00:09:30,206
There's a little bit of a spike there because in August alone, which was our highest month, we did receive 70 complaints.

90
00:09:31,707 --> 00:09:35,249
October and September have been a little bit better.

91
00:09:35,329 --> 00:09:38,992
So we're still playing catch up on some of those complaints.

92
00:09:40,352 --> 00:09:47,753
We also do GIS mapping of all of our complaints with the help of our folks in the engineering department.

93
00:09:47,773 --> 00:09:48,374
They've been great.

94
00:09:49,274 --> 00:09:51,794
So we try to use that to identify hotspots.

95
00:09:52,154 --> 00:09:56,555
So we see where there's a cluster of issues or complaints.

96
00:09:57,015 --> 00:10:08,858
We're able to go into those neighborhoods and areas and see what the contributing factors might be, whether it's a food source, water source, harborage, whether it's residential, commercial, dumpster related.

97
00:10:10,418 --> 00:10:11,579
food establishment related.

98
00:10:12,879 --> 00:10:17,341
And then we'll do a fly campaign in those neighborhoods where we see problems identified.

99
00:10:17,761 --> 00:10:32,227
Just again, trying to educate folks that bird feeders, feeding the wildlife, inappropriate composting, trash barrels that have holes, anything that can be a water or a food source or a hot bridge.

100
00:10:32,927 --> 00:10:38,610
We're trying to educate folks to understand that those are contributing factors to our issues.

101
00:10:39,846 --> 00:10:48,497
And we've done a really beefed up, increased enforcement of our dumpsters and looking at residential food and water sources.

102
00:10:52,931 --> 00:11:08,121
So our next steps, we are currently undergoing a thorough review of how to improve our processes and maybe some improvements we can make even to the Voting Control Ordinance and to our program.

103
00:11:09,882 --> 00:11:14,723
We're looking at additional options we did a survey of surrounding communities.

104
00:11:14,923 --> 00:11:22,445
Again, this is not just a method issue we're all like a lot of most urban communities are dealing with this increased rodent issue.

105
00:11:23,025 --> 00:11:30,306
So we did do a survey of neighboring communities to see if they were doing anything different that we weren't doing or that we could do.

106
00:11:31,487 --> 00:11:36,708
For the most part, everyone's trying to do the same thing as far as residential and commercial property education, and

107
00:11:38,209 --> 00:11:45,134
trying to seek compliance, and most other communities have also partnered with a pest control company.

108
00:11:45,634 --> 00:11:59,845
Some are using different methods that we may start to investigate and look at using going forward, because it seems like if you do multiple kind of abatement issues, that might help a little bit more.

109
00:12:01,105 --> 00:12:10,190
We also do have interdepartmental committee committee with DPW engineering, building and planning and development occasions.

110
00:12:11,282 --> 00:12:30,239
just to see how we all can contribute and some good ideas came out of our last meeting that we're going to set to formulate into a plan, maybe looking for additional like flyers right now the IPM is only asked for a permanent dumpsters, but we have a lot of temporary dumpster folks permits that we do.

111
00:12:31,280 --> 00:12:40,165
So maybe giving education and apply it to our temporary dumpster holders on do's and don'ts and what can go in that dumpster and what shouldn't go in that dumpster.

112
00:12:41,466 --> 00:12:52,253
Looking at our parks to really kind of investigate what's going on there, maybe additional signage, reminding people about, you know, trash and litter and how to pick up.

113
00:12:53,433 --> 00:12:59,037
Looking at maybe possibly a multi-stage installation of

114
00:13:00,415 --> 00:13:10,231
different barrels instead of the open top barrels, trying to move to a closed top barrel that rodents are unable to get into and feed.

115
00:13:12,543 --> 00:13:37,430
maybe requiring IPMs or permits maybe for the for composting so we know where the composting is at and then make sure that you know I know the city's moving towards a formal composting program and those that program does include rodent proof containers, but not all folks do that so really working with those folks who want to compost and how to do it right.

116
00:13:38,663 --> 00:13:51,231
Also looking at our culverts and overflows, again, as areas of water sources and harborages for rodents, really starting an inspection program around those areas.

117
00:13:53,261 --> 00:13:57,704
And, you know, in beefing up our communications and website information as well.

118
00:13:58,925 --> 00:14:04,349
We are continuing our residential education efforts on food and water sources.

119
00:14:05,230 --> 00:14:09,173
Unfortunately, you have a lot of residents who

120
00:14:10,233 --> 00:14:19,599
really find joy in feeding the birds and the wildlife, but unfortunately that is a huge contributing factor to the problem.

121
00:14:20,620 --> 00:14:38,091
So we are trying to educate our residents on the problems that are associated with bird feeding and feeding the wildlife, as well as, again, improper composting, unkept gardens, you know, making sure that fruit and vegetables and

122
00:14:39,212 --> 00:14:41,373
are picked up and kept up.

123
00:14:43,514 --> 00:14:50,017
Unfortunately, we do find that sometimes it's difficult to get compliance and for people to understand.

124
00:14:51,717 --> 00:15:01,742
And so unfortunately, that does mean that Board of Health has to issue citations and fines when compliance isn't obtained.

125
00:15:03,309 --> 00:15:08,332
